Excellent, thank you. Now... where were we?  Ah, I'm reviewing the Live Data Architecture Diagram.  Now... a couple of issues I'm seeing, to go along with your own observations, but
  perhaps mosre simplistically though more directly to the point and purpose of the system: "Bridge Lua -> SSH+JSON -> Watcher ETL" should be describing a pipeline in which the live
  capturedata goes into structured data files on disk and then from these on-disk files a second pipeline will further ETL into data tables of our Chronicler database.  This leads to the
  second point, being that those "Live Tables" and raw dump dead end "lua_probes" are all in a sense dead ends because they aren't being FULLY transformed into the already existing CDM to
  fit INTO the already existing tables.  You have rightly highlighted this issue as [X NO CONNECTION].  There is no purpose to keeping these non-connected data tables, but instead the
  live-streamed data -> on-disk structured files -> Chronicler DB should be designed so that the data goes all the way INTO those core data tables which are already wired into the UI,
  and/or which can easily be wired up without greatly reshaping the "Legends Tables" CDM.  What I consider the ACTUAL Chronicler database is what you have labelled as the "Legends Tables"
  and so EVERY in-game data structure that is live streamed through the Live Capture Pipeline MUST have as its end-point a location within THESE tables.  If, for any reason you cannot
  decide on a feasible way to transform and ingest an in-game data structure then you must flag these data structures and objects for co-review with me.  Any redesign of the CDM beyond what is currently in the Legends Tables should be considered scope creep and may only be done with my explicit permissions.  You must create diagrams of your reasoning and of your design plan and of your implementation plan and review these as part of your self-assessment of work.

  There is also another misconception revealed in the design diagram.  The XML imports needs to be revised as follows:
  1) It MUST take a pre-embark Legends XML AND Legends Plus XML as the initial input.  This is a ONE TIME data ingestion event.
  2) It MAY take post-embark Legends XML AND/OR Legends Plus XML as additional input. A 'diff' on pre-post embark XMLs will reveal new data that MUST be ingested into the database as
  updates or appened information, as is appropriate for a given data object.  This is an OPTIONAL MANY TIMES data ingestion event.
  3) This section of the diagram should be annotated with the DFhack exportlegends and open-legends functions as the functions/triggers that create those XMLs.  Also update the rest of the
  diagram with the relevant script or function that runs each particular stage of the overall pipeline.
  
  I generally agree with your assessment that "The architecture diagram makes the problem visually clear:

  - Top: Live game data flows down through the Bridge → Watcher → into the orange Live Tables (right side) and the red lua_probes dead end (left-center)
  - Bottom-left: Legends XML flows through a one-time import into the blue Legends Tables
  - Bottom: The green Web UI queries ONLY the blue Legends Tables via SELECT
  - Right edge: The critical "❌ NO CONNECTION" label between Live Tables and Legends Tables

  The two data worlds sit side by side in the same database but never communicate. The UI reads from legends, live data writes to its own tables, and the user sees a frozen snapshot from
  worldgen.

  The fix is that dotted line — turning it into a solid connection where the watcher's post-ingest step propagates deaths, events, and membership changes back into the legends tables that the UI already queries."  However I want to stress that EVERY in-game data structure that is live streamed through the Live Capture Pipeline MUST have as its end-point a location within the Legends Tables.

  Make these changes to your design, generate a design plan, implementation plan, and diagram of the updated architecture.  Review and revise your plans if you notice anything incomplete like any data left hanging which does not make it into the core Legends Tables of the database CDM for example.








